                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: Introduction
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-intro">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <!-- nav top -->
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-install">← Installation and startup</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-guide-workflow-state-mapping">State mapping →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">Step-by-step Guide</p>
                        <h2>Introduction</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Every nOS application is assembled from three fundamental building blocks:
                        <strong>Node</strong>, <strong>Workflow</strong> and <strong>Link</strong>.
                        Understanding how they relate to each other is the starting point for building
                        any automation — from a single-step data transformer to a multi-agent pipeline.
                    </p>

                    <div class="nos-blocks-grid">

                        <!-- Node -->
                        <div class="nos-block-card">
                            <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="4"/><path d="M12 2v2M12 20v2M4.93 4.93l1.41 1.41M17.66 17.66l1.41 1.41M2 12h2M20 12h2M4.93 19.07l1.41-1.41M17.66 6.34l1.41-1.41"/></svg>
                                <span class="nos-block-card-title">Node</span>
                            </div>
                            <p class="nos-block-card-body">
                                A <strong>Node</strong> is the atomic unit of work in nOS. It encapsulates a
                                self-contained, reusable piece of logic: it receives typed inputs —
                                a <strong>state</strong> (shared context inherited from the workflow) and
                                <strong>parameters</strong> (node-specific configuration) — executes a task, and
                                returns a structured <strong>output</strong>.<br><br>
                                Nodes can be <em>deterministic</em> (pure functions, data transforms, API calls),
                                <em>AI-powered</em> (model inference, classification, generation) or
                                <em>agentic</em> (autonomous decision-making, tool use, multi-step reasoning).
                                Each node defines its own input and output schemas, which the framework uses
                                for validation, form generation and documentation. The core method to implement
                                is <code>_do_execute(state, params)</code>, which returns a <code>NodeOutput</code>.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <!-- Workflow -->
                        <div class="nos-block-card">
                            <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><rect x="2" y="7" width="6" height="4" rx="1"/><rect x="16" y="7" width="6" height="4" rx="1"/><rect x="9" y="14" width="6" height="4" rx="1"/><path d="M8 9h3l1 5h-2M16 9h-3l-1 5h2"/></svg>
                                <span class="nos-block-card-title">Workflow</span>
                            </div>
                            <p class="nos-block-card-body">
                                A <strong>Workflow</strong> is a directed graph of nodes. It defines the
                                execution order, data flow and branching logic between nodes, turning isolated
                                units of work into a coherent, repeatable process.<br><br>
                                Workflows share a common <strong>state</strong> dictionary that nodes can read
                                from and write to as execution progresses. A workflow exposes the same execution
                                interfaces as a single node — REST API, WebSocket, Webhook, MCP — and generates
                                the same structured execution log, making the entire pipeline observable end to end.
                                Workflows are defined programmatically by implementing the <code>define()</code>
                                method and registering nodes together with their links.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <!-- Link -->
                        <div class="nos-block-card">
                            <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="5" cy="12" r="2.5"/><circle cx="19" cy="12" r="2.5"/><path d="M7.5 12h9"/><polyline points="13.5 8.5 17 12 13.5 15.5"/></svg>
                                <span class="nos-block-card-title">Link</span>
                            </div>
                            <p class="nos-block-card-body">
                                A <strong>Link</strong> is the directed connection between two nodes within a
                                workflow. It routes the output of a <em>source</em> node to the input of a
                                <em>target</em> node, optionally applying a <strong>state mapping</strong> to
                                control exactly which fields are forwarded and how they are transformed.<br><br>
                                Links can carry conditional logic — enabling branching, fan-out and fan-in
                                patterns — and are the primary mechanism through which the workflow's shared
                                state evolves as execution moves from node to node. Defining links explicitly
                                keeps data flow visible, auditable and easy to reason about.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                    </div>

                    <!-- nav bottom -->
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-install">← Installation and startup</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-guide-workflow-state-mapping">State mapping →</a>
                    </nav>

                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
