            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — EventLogBuffer / EventLog (execution sinks overview)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-event-log-sinks">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run">← <code>Workflow.run</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-client-integration-intro">Open execution →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API</p>
                        <h2>EventLogBuffer / EventLog</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Every run needs an <strong>execution sink</strong>: something that collects structured events (progress, diagnostics, lifecycle)
                        and optionally delivers them to a client. In plugins you almost never touch the concrete class—you call
                        <strong><code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code></strong> on a <strong>node</strong> or <strong><code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code></strong> on a <strong>workflow</strong>.
                        The engine attaches the right implementation before your code runs.
                    </p>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.65rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title"><code>EventLogBuffer</code> (core, in-process)</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>What it does</strong> — Keeps events in memory, appends them to the API/CLI result (<code>event_logs</code>), and mirrors a short text line to Python <code>logging</code> (typically <code>INFO</code>) for local debugging.</li>
                            <li><strong>When you get it</strong> — <code>Node.run</code> / <code>Workflow.run</code> with <code>exec_log=None</code>, REST-style runs without a Socket.IO room, tests, and <code>python -m …</code> scripts. The engine creates a default buffer if you do not pass one.</li>
                            <li><strong>What it does <em>not</em> do</strong> — No live WebSocket stream; no <code>request_and_wait</code> for interactive forms (those need the platform sink below).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.65rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 12v8a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2v-8"/><polyline points="16 6 12 2 8 6"/><line x1="12" y1="2" x2="12" y2="15"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title"><code>EventLog</code> (platform)</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>What it does</strong> — Same event model as the buffer, plus <strong>real-time delivery</strong> to connected clients (e.g. Console / embedded UI over Socket.IO), persistence hooks where configured, and interactive primitives such as <code>request_and_wait</code> for forms.</li>
                            <li><strong>When you get it</strong> — Runs started through the web console, engine Socket.IO flow, or any path that builds an <code>EventLog</code> with a client <code>room</code>. Workflow/node <code>debug_mode</code> interacts with per-node forms only when this sink (or an equivalent realtime channel) is in use.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>What to write in a node plugin</strong></p>
                    <p style="font-size:0.88rem;line-height:1.72">
                        Use <code>self.exec_log.log</code> inside <code>_do_execute</code> (or after <code>super()</code> in lifecycle hooks) for anything operators should see in the execution timeline—steps completed, counts, warnings. The same calls work for both sinks; only transport and interactivity differ.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _do_execute(self, state_dict: dict, params_dict: dict) -&gt; NodeOutput:
    self.exec_log.log(
        "info",
        "Parsing input",
        event="parse_start",
        rows=len(state_dict.get("items", [])),
    )
    # ... work ...
    self.exec_log.log("info", "Done", event="parse_done")
    return NodeOutput(output={"output_format": "json", "data": {"ok": True}})</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>Workflow plugins</strong></p>
                    <p style="font-size:0.88rem;line-height:1.72">
                        Hooks such as <code>_on_start</code> can use <code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code> once the engine has attached the workflow log (same pattern as nodes). Prefer this for <em>workflow-level</em> messages; node steps should log from inside each node.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_start(self, initial_state=None):
    super()._on_start(initial_state)
    self.exec_log.log("info", f"Workflow {self.workflow_id} entering run", event="wf_start")</code></pre>

                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0.85rem">
                        <strong>Scripts and tests.</strong> Buffer-backed runs mirror to the <code>nos.core.execution_log.event_log_buffer</code> logger at <code>INFO</code>.
                        If nothing appears in the terminal, configure logging (e.g. <code>logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO)</code>) or read
                        <code>result.event_logs</code> / <code>NodeExecutionResult.event_logs</code> on the returned object.
                    </p>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        <strong>Deeper reference</strong> — Property <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log" href="#"><code>exec_log</code></a> (Node),
                        method <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log" href="#"><code>log</code></a>, and
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview" href="#">Event handling → Overview</a>.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run">← <code>Workflow.run</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-client-integration-intro">Open execution →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — Open execution (client integration overview)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-client-integration-intro">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks">← EventLogBuffer / EventLog</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-client-integration-rest">REST API →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Open execution</p>
                        <h2>Introduction</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Nodes and workflows are not confined to the built-in console: execution is a <strong>first-class surface</strong> you can call from your own systems.
                        Whether you need a straightforward <strong>request–response</strong> integration or a <strong>live, bidirectional</strong> experience, the same engine backs both paths.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        You can <strong>invoke node and workflow runs from an external application via the REST API</strong>—ideal for batch jobs, microservices, and server-side orchestration—
                        or go further and <strong>embed an interactive UI</strong> that streams progress, logs, and form prompts over <strong>Socket.IO</strong>, matching the richness of the native console without leaving your product shell.
                    </p>
                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:1rem">
                        The following sections document concrete REST endpoints and Socket.IO events; those pages are placeholders until the reference is expanded.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks">← EventLogBuffer / EventLog</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-client-integration-rest">REST API →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — REST API (stub)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-client-integration-rest">
