            <div class="nos-page" id="section-output-formats">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-set-default-state-mapping">← set_default_state_mapping</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-adapters-input-form-mapping"><code>input_form_mapping</code> →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Adapters (WebUI)</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>output_format_schema</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        <code>OUTPUT_FORMATS</code> lists every key the engine and Web console accept for rendering
                        <code>NodeOutput.output["data"]</code> / workflow results.
                        Each node may restrict allowed values with <code>ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS</code>.
                    </p>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0 0 0.35rem">From <code>_do_execute</code> — shape <code>data</code> for the format you use (or omit <code>output_format</code> in the dict and rely on <code>default_output_format</code> / the caller):</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">from nos.core.engine.base import NodeOutput

# Table: columns + rows (see table row in the reference below)
return NodeOutput(
    output={
        "output_format": "table",
        "data": {
            "columns": ["id", "label"],
            "rows": [
                {"id": 1, "label": "alpha"},
                {"id": 2, "label": "beta"},
            ],
        },
    }
)

# JSON (default family): any serializable payload
return NodeOutput(
    output={"output_format": "json", "data": {"status": "ok", "items": 42}},
)</code></pre>

                    <table class="nos-index-table" aria-label="output_format_schema">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="col">Format</th>
                                <th scope="col">HTML rendering</th>
                                <th scope="col">Payload structure</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>json</code></td>
                                <td>Collapsible key–value tree (DevTools-style).</td>
                                <td>Any JSON-serializable value (<code>dict</code>, <code>list</code>, scalar).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>text</code></td>
                                <td>Standalone <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> block (<code>cmd-text-content</code>); whitespace preserved.</td>
                                <td><strong>String</strong> — plain text body. (The console treats non-string <code>data</code> as incompatible and falls back to JSON view.)</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>html</code></td>
                                <td>Injected as HTML after sanitization (<code>sanitizeHtml</code>).</td>
                                <td><strong>String</strong> — HTML snippet. (Same string requirement in the console validator as <code>text</code>.)</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>table</code></td>
                                <td><code>&lt;table&gt;</code> with sortable columns; footer actions export <strong>CSV</strong>, <strong>JSON</strong>, <strong>Excel</strong>.</td>
                                <td><code>{"columns": ["col1", ...], "rows": [{"col1": v, ...}, ...]}</code>. List-of-lists rows are normalized to dicts server-side when column names are present.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>code</code></td>
                                <td><code>&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;</code>; Prism highlight when <code>language</code> is set and available.</td>
                                <td><code>{"code": "...", "language": "python"}</code> per <code>OutputCodeSchema</code>; a bare <strong>string</strong> is coerced server-side for validation. The console expects a <strong>string</strong> <code>data</code> for the code panel — object payloads fall back to JSON tree until normalized client-side.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>tree</code></td>
                                <td><code>&lt;pre class="file-tree"&gt;</code> (monospace path-style presentation).</td>
                                <td><code>{"name": "...", "children": [...]}</code> (recursive). Non-string content is escaped / stringified for display.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>chart</code></td>
                                <td>Inline SVG chart + type selector: <code>bar</code>, <code>line</code>, <code>pie</code>, <code>doughnut</code>.</td>
                                <td><code>{"type"?: "...", "labels": [...], "values": [...]}</code> and/or Chart.js-style <code>"datasets"</code> (see <code>OutputChartSchema</code>).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>download</code></td>
                                <td>Styled primary download link (icon, filename, optional size).</td>
                                <td><code>{"url": "...", "filename"?: "...", "size"?: int}</code> (<code>size</code> = file size in bytes). <code>url</code> required.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-set-default-state-mapping">← set_default_state_mapping</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-adapters-input-form-mapping"><code>input_form_mapping</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Adapters (WebUI) — input_form_mapping (stub)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-adapters-input-form-mapping">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-output-formats">← <code>output_format_schema</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-execution-outcomes">Execution outcomes &amp; errors →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Adapters (WebUI)</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>input_form_mapping</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0">
                        <em>Coming soon.</em> This section will describe how node/workflow input is mapped to Web UI form fields and validation.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-output-formats">← <code>output_format_schema</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-execution-outcomes">Execution outcomes &amp; errors →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — Execution outcomes & errors (node status + workflow)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-execution-outcomes">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-adapters-input-form-mapping">← <code>input_form_mapping</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-init"><code>Node.__init__</code> →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API</p>
                        <h2>Execution outcomes &amp; errors</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;line-height:1.75;max-width:52rem">
                        This reference maps <strong>how failures surface</strong> so you can debug plugins and integrations without reading the engine line-by-line.
                        <strong>Nodes</strong> normally return a <code>NodeExecutionResult</code> with a string <code>status</code> and details under <code>response.output["data"]</code> (often a <code>detail</code> or <code>reason</code> field).
                        <strong>Workflows</strong> return <code>WorkflowExecutionResult</code> with <code>status</code> <code>"success"</code> or <code>"cancelled"</code> when the run finishes inside the engine; many <strong>hard failures</strong> still arrive as <strong>Python exceptions</strong> from <code>Workflow.run</code> / <code>execute_sync</code>—catch them at the call site.
                    </p>

                    <h3 style="font-size:1.05rem;margin:1.25rem 0 0.5rem;font-weight:600">Node execution (<code>NodeExecutionResult.status</code>)</h3>
                    <table class="nos-index-table" aria-label="Node execution outcomes">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="col">Code</th>
                                <th scope="col">Meaning</th>
                                <th scope="col">What happens &amp; how to fix</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>completed</code></td>
                                <td>Success</td>
                                <td>The node finished normally. Use <code>response.output</code> (<code>output_format</code> + <code>data</code>) and optional <code>metadata</code>. No fix required.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>cancelled</code></td>
                                <td>Stopped cooperatively</td>
                                <td>The run ended early by design: user cancelled an interactive form, <code>_on_start</code> returned a value other than exactly <code>True</code>, or a stop was requested and the next <code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code> raised <code>CancellationError</code> (handled for you). Inspect <code>response.output["data"]</code> for <code>reason</code> / <code>detail</code>. To implement “stop”: use the engine/console stop flow—do not swallow <code>CancellationError</code> unless you know you need a custom path.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>validation_error</code></td>
                                <td>Input validation failed</td>
                                <td>State or parameters failed Pydantic validation during init, or the user-submitted debug form failed re-validation. Read <code>response.output["data"]["detail"]</code>. Align caller payloads with <code>input_state_schema</code> / <code>input_params_schema</code>, or fix the form-backed fields.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>form_validation_error</code></td>
                                <td>Interactive form path failed</td>
                                <td>Something went wrong while showing or processing the debug-mode form (e.g. transport error), not a simple field validation message. Check <code>detail</code> in the response payload and the execution <code>event_logs</code>. Ensure a realtime <code>EventLog</code> sink when using <code>debug_mode="debug"</code> with forms.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>output_validation_error</code></td>
                                <td>Output shape mismatch</td>
                                <td><code>_do_execute</code> returned data that does not satisfy <code>output_schema</code> / <code>metadata_schema</code>. Adjust the returned <code>NodeOutput</code> to match your declared models (or relax schemas intentionally).</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>internal_error</code></td>
                                <td>Unexpected failure after init</td>
                                <td>An exception escaped <code>_do_execute</code>, the return value was not a <code>NodeOutput</code>, or another post-init bug occurred. Read <code>detail</code> (and server logs / <code>event_logs</code>). Fix the implementation; add <code>try/except</code> inside <code>_do_execute</code> only if you want a <em>business-level</em> error returned as normal output instead of this status.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>bad_request</code></td>
                                <td>Early request / hook rejection</td>
                                <td><code>ValueError</code> or Pydantic validation was raised from <code>_on_start</code> while building the run envelope. Fix the <code>request</code> dict shape or the hook logic.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    <h3 style="font-size:1.05rem;margin:1.35rem 0 0.5rem;font-weight:600">Workflow execution (<code>WorkflowExecutionResult</code> &amp; exceptions)</h3>
                    <table class="nos-index-table" aria-label="Workflow execution outcomes">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="col">Code / signal</th>
                                <th scope="col">Meaning</th>
                                <th scope="col">What happens &amp; how to fix</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>status == "success"</code></td>
                                <td>Workflow completed the graph</td>
                                <td>Final shared state passed validation where applicable; see <code>response.output</code>, <code>state</code>, <code>state_changed</code>, <code>node_ids_executed</code>. No fix required.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>status == "cancelled"</code></td>
                                <td>Workflow stopped early</td>
                                <td>Either the user cancelled the <em>initial</em> workflow state form (platform sink), or a <strong>node step</strong> returned <code>NodeExecutionResult</code> with <code>status="cancelled"</code>. Use <code>result.message</code> and metadata for context. Adjust UX or node logic if cancellation was unintended.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>ValueError</code> (raised)</td>
                                <td>Configuration or state rejected</td>
                                <td>Common cases: invalid <code>output_format</code> for the engine, initial workflow form data failing <code>state_schema</code>, or shared state after a node failing <code>validate_state_or_raise</code> (node output incompatible with workflow state). Fix the offending format string, schemas, or the upstream node’s state updates.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><code>RuntimeError</code> (raised)</td>
                                <td>Safety limit hit</td>
                                <td>The engine aborted because the workflow exceeded the maximum step count (infinite or overly long loop in the graph). Review links and entry/exit conditions.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Other <code>Exception</code> (raised)</td>
                                <td>Unhandled error inside a step</td>
                                <td>A node step threw an exception that was not converted into a structured <code>NodeExecutionResult</code> (or an error occurred outside the node’s normal result path). The workflow marks itself in error and the exception propagates to your <code>run</code> / <code>execute_sync</code> caller. Read the traceback; fix the node, link, or workflow code.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:1rem">
                        For logging and cooperative cancellation from plugins, see
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks" href="#">EventLogBuffer / EventLog</a> and
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-cooperative-stop" href="#"><code>request_cooperative_stop</code></a>.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-adapters-input-form-mapping">← <code>input_form_mapping</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-init"><code>Node.__init__</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — Node __init__ (constructor)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-init">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-intro">← Introduction</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-default-output-format">default_output_format →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>__init__</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Constructor for every <code>Node</code> subclass. The engine or registry passes a stable
                        <strong><code>node_id</code></strong> (used in logs, execution context and CLI <code>run node …</code>);
                        <strong><code>name</code></strong> is optional display metadata and defaults to <code>node_id</code>.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def __init__(self, node_id: str, name: str = None):
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Initial state</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>self.node_id</code></strong> / <strong><code>self.name</code></strong> — set from arguments; subclasses rarely need to override <code>__init__</code> unless they add validated instance configuration (call <code>super().__init__(node_id, name=name)</code> first).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>_exec_log</code></strong> — <code>None</code> until <code>set_exec_log</code>; use the public <code>self.exec_log</code> property in node code.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>_debug_mode</code></strong> — toggled by the platform for interactive forms before <code>_do_execute</code>; do not set manually from plugins.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>_default_state_mapping</code></strong> / <strong><code>_run_event_hook</code></strong> — managed by the framework (state mapping and per-run hook bus).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-intro">← Introduction</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-default-output-format">default_output_format →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — default_output_format (in-page reference)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-default-output-format">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-init">← <code>__init__</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-params-schema">input_params_schema →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">default_output_format</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        When the caller does not pass <code>output_format</code> (CLI/API) and <code>NodeOutput.output</code> omits it,
                        the engine uses this member as the fallback: a <strong>string</strong> key naming how <code>response.output["data"]</code> should be interpreted.
                        The base class uses <code>"json"</code>; subclasses override when the natural result is another format (e.g. <code>"code"</code>, <code>"html"</code>).
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def default_output_format(self) -> str:
    return "json"</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Resolution order</strong> — effective format is <code>CLI --output_format</code> (or API <code>output_format</code> on the execute request, or <code>Node.run(..., output_format=…)</code>) if set, else <code>output["output_format"]</code> from <code>_do_execute</code>, else <code>default_output_format</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong>allowed_output_formats()</strong> — the default string must be one of the values returned here; restrict with <code>ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS</code> if you narrow formats.</li>
                            <li><strong>Rendering</strong> — drives how the console/UI interprets <code>response.output["data"]</code> when no higher-priority format is chosen.</li>
                            <li><strong>Not a schema</strong> — unlike <code>input_params_schema</code>, this only names a format key; the shape of <code>data</code> still follows the contract for that format (see output formats docs).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        In code, implement it as a read-only property on the subclass when the node’s primary artifact is not JSON (e.g. code blocks, HTML preview, tables).
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-init">← <code>__init__</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-params-schema">input_params_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — input_params_schema (in-page reference)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-input-params-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-default-output-format">← default_output_format</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-state-schema">input_state_schema →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">input_params_schema</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>Pydantic v2 <code>BaseModel</code></strong> type describing direct parameters for a node.
                        The engine validates <code>input_params</code> before <code>_do_execute</code>; returning <code>None</code> defers to a flat pass-through schema.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def input_params_schema(self) -> Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Execution payload</strong> — JSON field <code>input_params</code> on REST <code>/api/node/execute*</code> must match declared model fields; unknown keys are rejected when a schema is set.</li>
                            <li><strong>CLI / automation</strong> — <code>--param name=value</code> maps into the same validated dict; field names are the model attributes.</li>
                            <li><strong>Console &amp; forms</strong> — interactive runs use this schema (with <code>input_state_schema</code>) to build the parameter form and pre-fill defaults from the model.</li>
                            <li><strong>State separation</strong> — keys in <code>input_params</code> must not overlap workflow <code>state</code> keys; collisions raise before execution.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        Implement on your node subclass: return a concrete <code>BaseModel</code> subclass (or <code>None</code>). Same pattern as <code>input_state_schema</code> / <code>output_schema</code> for typed IO across API, CLI and UI.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-default-output-format">← default_output_format</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-state-schema">input_state_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — input_state_schema (in-page reference)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-input-state-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-params-schema">← input_params_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-output-schema">output_schema →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">input_state_schema</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>Pydantic v2 <code>BaseModel</code></strong> type describing workflow / context <strong>state</strong> passed into the node.
                        The engine validates <code>state</code> before <code>_do_execute</code>; returning <code>None</code> defers to a flat pass-through schema.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def input_state_schema(self) -> Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Execution payload</strong> — JSON field <code>state</code> on REST <code>/api/node/execute*</code> supplies the workflow context; it is validated against this model when defined.</li>
                            <li><strong>CLI / automation</strong> — Web CLI <code>run node …</code> accepts repeatable <code>--state key=value</code>; values merge into the same validated state dict, with field names matching the model attributes.</li>
                            <li><strong>Workflows</strong> — shared workflow state is mapped into node state via <code>StateMapping</code>; the node still sees a validated dict matching <code>input_state_schema</code> when set.</li>
                            <li><strong>Console &amp; forms</strong> — debug / interactive runs use this schema (with <code>input_params_schema</code>) to build the state section of the form and apply defaults.</li>
                            <li><strong>Parameter separation</strong> — keys in <code>state</code> must not overlap <code>input_params</code>; collisions raise during init before execution.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        Implement on your node subclass: return a concrete <code>BaseModel</code> subclass (or <code>None</code>). Same pattern as <code>input_params_schema</code>, <code>output_schema</code> and <code>metadata_schema</code> for typed IO across API, CLI and UI.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-params-schema">← input_params_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-output-schema">output_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — output_schema (in-page reference)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-output-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-state-schema">← input_state_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log">exec_log →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Properties</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">output_schema</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>Pydantic v2 <code>BaseModel</code></strong> describing the shape of the primary payload <code>data</code> inside <code>NodeOutput.output</code> (same keys as everywhere else: <code>output_format</code> + <code>data</code>).
                        After <code>_do_execute</code>, when <code>data</code> is a <code>dict</code> and a schema is set, the engine validates it with this model; returning <code>None</code> skips structural validation of that payload (format-specific rules still apply).
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def output_schema(self) -> Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>Result nesting</strong> — same pattern as the workflow: the renderable slice is always <code>{"output_format", "data"}</code>; <code>output_schema</code> constrains <code>data</code> only. <code>_do_execute</code> returns a <code>NodeOutput</code>; the full run is a <code>NodeExecutionResult</code> whose <code>response</code> mirrors that shape (plus <code>metadata</code>).</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">from typing import Optional, Type
from pydantic import BaseModel, Field
from nos.core.engine import Node, NodeExecutionResult, NodeOutput, NodeResponseData


class MyNodeResult(BaseModel):
    """Validated shape of NodeOutput.output['data'] when output_schema returns this model."""
    user_id: str
    score: float = Field(..., ge=0)


class MyNode(Node):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__(node_id="my_node", name="My node")

    @property
    def output_schema(self) -> Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
        return MyNodeResult

    def _do_execute(self, state_dict, params_dict):
        # NodeOutput.output = { output_format, data }; output_schema validates data (dict)
        return NodeOutput(
            output={
                "output_format": "json",
                "data": {"user_id": "u1", "score": 42.0},
            },
            metadata={"elapsed_ms": 12},
        )


# After Node.execute — NodeExecutionResult (imports for typing / docs):
# NodeExecutionResult(
#     execution_id=..., node_id="my_node", status="completed",
#     response=NodeResponseData(
#         output={"output_format": "json", "data": {...}},  # same keys as NodeOutput.output
#         metadata={...},
#     ),
#     initial_state=..., final_state=..., event_logs=..., ...
# )</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>NodeOutput.output["data"]</code></strong> / <strong><code>NodeExecutionResult.response.output["data"]</code></strong> — same field; validated when it is a <code>dict</code> and <code>output_schema</code> is set.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>metadata_schema</code></strong> — validates <code>NodeOutput.metadata</code> and <code>response.metadata</code> separately.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>output_format</code></strong> — how <code>data</code> is rendered (JSON, table, etc.) is independent of this model; see <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-output-formats" href="#"><code>output_format_schema</code></a>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Validation errors</strong> — failures surface as <code>output_validation_error</code> on the execution result.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        Implement on your node subclass: return a concrete <code>BaseModel</code> subclass (or <code>None</code>). Same pattern as <code>input_params_schema</code> / <code>input_state_schema</code> / <code>metadata_schema</code> for typed IO across API, CLI and UI.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-input-state-schema">← input_state_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log">exec_log →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — exec_log (property; event handling docs)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-exec-log">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-output-schema">← output_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-metadata-schema">metadata_schema →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">exec_log</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Conceptual overview: <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks" href="#">EventLogBuffer / EventLog</a> (when each sink is used and how to log from plugins).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Read-only access to the <strong>execution log</strong> for node code. The engine calls <code>set_exec_log</code> with an <code>EventLogBuffer</code> or platform <code>EventLog</code>; from subclasses you use <strong><code>self.exec_log</code></strong>, a <strong><code>NodeExecLog</code></strong> wrapper.
                        It exposes only what plugin authors need for logging; framework events (<code>log_node_init</code>, <code>log_node_end</code>, …) stay on the base class.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def exec_log(self) -> NodeExecLog:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.75rem 0 0.35rem">Example — append to the execution event log from <code>_do_execute</code> (traceability, diagnostics):</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _do_execute(self, state_dict, params_dict):
    self.exec_log.log(
        "info",
        "Starting processing",
        event="processing_start",
        item_count=len(state_dict.get("items", [])),
    )
    # ... work ...
    self.exec_log.log(
        "debug",
        "Checkpoint reached",
        phase="normalize",
    )
    return NodeOutput(
        output={"output_format": "json", "data": {"status": "ok"}},
    )</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Event handling</span>
                        </div>
                        <p class="nos-block-card-body" style="margin:0;font-size:0.86rem;line-height:1.72">
                            Execution emits a structured event stream (real-time where supported, persisted on the result). Start with
                            <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview" href="#">Event handling → Overview</a>;
                            for plugin-authored messages use <strong><code>self.exec_log.log</code></strong> —
                            <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log" href="#">Event log</a>.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-output-schema">← output_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-metadata-schema">metadata_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Event handling — Overview
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-overview">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log">← exec_log</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start"><code>_on_start</code> →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">Overview</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0">
                        Execution sinks (buffer vs platform): <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks" href="#">EventLogBuffer / EventLog</a>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <strong>Event handling</strong> is how nOS makes node execution <em>observable</em>: the engine and your code emit
                        structured events that describe progress, decisions, diagnostics, and outcomes. Together they form an
                        <strong>event log</strong> you can use for live monitoring, auditing, and troubleshooting—without overloading the
                        primary <code>NodeOutput</code> payload.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        When execution runs through interactive paths (for example the Console with a connected client), compatible
                        channels can <strong>deliver events in real time</strong>, so operators see informational messages, warnings, and
                        errors as they occur.                         The same sequence is also <strong>persisted on the execution result</strong>: it is recorded in
                        <code>NodeExecutionResult.event_logs</code> (and exposed through related APIs), so REST responses, stored runs,
                        and downstream tooling retain a complete <strong>trace</strong> for later review, auditing, and compliance.
                    </p>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">What you get</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Severity and intent</strong> — Events carry levels such as <code>debug</code>, <code>info</code>, <code>warning</code>, and <code>error</code>, aligned with logging practice so you can filter noise from actionable signals.</li>
                            <li><strong>Framework vs custom</strong> — The base <code>Node</code> class emits lifecycle and system events; plugin code typically adds context via <code>self.exec_log.log</code> (see <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log" href="#">Event log</a>).</li>
                            <li><strong>Lifecycle hooks</strong> — Override <code>_on_*</code> methods so the engine runs your logic at fixed phases; the base implementation forwards lifecycle signals to the execution log (<code>node_start</code>, <code>node_end</code>, <code>node_error</code>, <code>node.stop</code> / <code>_on_stop</code> for cooperative cancel, etc.). Reference pages in this menu run <code>_on_start</code> … <code>_on_error</code>, <code>_on_stop</code>, then <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log" href="#">Event log</a>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Debugging and trace</strong> — Rich, ordered logs make it easier to correlate state, parameters, and failures across a single run or an entire workflow.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        From node code, the public entry point is the <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log" href="#"><code>exec_log</code></a> property; CLI-only runs use a no-op execution log—<code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code> and related calls are safe no-ops.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log">← exec_log</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start"><code>_on_start</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Event handling · exec_log — log (NodeExecLog.log)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-exec-log-log">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-stop">← <code>_on_stop</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-event-hook-manager">Event hook manager →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · exec_log</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>log</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0">
                        See <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks" href="#">EventLogBuffer / EventLog</a> for buffer vs platform behaviour before diving into parameters.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Method on <code>NodeExecLog</code> — use <code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code> inside <code>_do_execute</code> and other node methods. Builds a <code>CustomEvent</code>, appends it to the execution buffer, mirrors to Python logging, and when the underlying <code>EventLog</code> has realtime delivery enabled, pushes the same payload to clients. Cooperative cancellation: if a stop was requested, <code>CancellationError</code> is raised before the event is recorded.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def log(
    self,
    level: str,
    message: str,
    *,
    event: str = "Logging event",
    include_base_fields: bool = True,
    **kwargs,
) -> None:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>level</code></strong> — <code>debug</code>, <code>info</code>, <code>warning</code>, <code>error</code> (mirrors log level).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>event</code></strong> — logical event name stored on <code>CustomEvent</code>; use stable strings for filtering (default <code>Logging event</code>, aligned with the Pydantic model).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>include_base_fields</code></strong> — when <code>True</code>, payload includes <code>execution_id</code>, <code>node_id</code>, timestamps, etc.; when <code>False</code>, only <code>level</code>, <code>message</code>, and <code>kwargs</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>**kwargs</code></strong> — extra fields merged into the event (avoid reserved logging keys).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>Node.exec_log</code></strong> — property that wraps the live buffer or a null object when no execution log is set (CLI).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-stop">← <code>_on_stop</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-event-hook-manager">Event hook manager →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Event handling — Event hook manager (node_run_hooks)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-event-hook-manager">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log">← <code>log</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview">Overview →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">Event hook manager (execution)</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        In everyday plugins you only need <strong>Event log</strong> (<code>self.exec_log.log</code>) and lifecycle hooks such as <code>_on_start</code>.
                        The code sample below is for tests, internal tools, or custom setups where you wire a log buffer and hook bus yourself.
                    </p>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.75rem 0 0.35rem">Example — hook your own callback, then fire a lifecycle event so it flows into the buffer:</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">from nos.hooks.manager import EventHookManager
from nos.core.execution_log.event_log_buffer import EventLogBuffer
from nos.core.execution_log.node_run_hooks import (
    NodeRunEventType,
    register_node_run_hooks_adapters,
)

exec_log = EventLogBuffer(
    execution_id="ex-demo",
    node_id="demo_node",
    module_path="my_plugin.nodes.demo",
    class_name="DemoNode",
)
bus = EventHookManager()

def trace_init(data: dict) -&gt; None:
    """Runs first; register before adapters if you need pre-emit side effects."""
    st = (data or {}).get("initial_state") or {}
    print("hook: init about to run, state keys =", list(st.keys()))

bus.register(NodeRunEventType.NODE_INIT, trace_init)
register_node_run_hooks_adapters(bus, exec_log)

bus.emit(
    NodeRunEventType.NODE_INIT,
    {
        "initial_state": {"count": 0},
        "initial_params": {"mode": "dry_run"},
    },
)

assert exec_log.get_events()[-1].event == "initializing"</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Reference</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>NodeRunEventType</code></strong> — <code>node.run</code>, <code>node.start</code>, <code>node.init</code>, <code>node.init_completed</code>, <code>node.form_response</code>, <code>node.state_changed</code>, <code>node.error</code>, <code>node.stop</code>, <code>node.end</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>register_node_run_hooks_adapters(bus, exec_log)</code></strong> — registers framework handlers that call <code>exec_log.log_*</code> for each type.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>attach_node_run_hooks_bus(node, exec_log)</code></strong> — creates a bus, registers adapters, <code>node.set_run_event_hook(bus)</code>; used from <code>Node.set_exec_log</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>EventHookManager.emit(event_type, data)</code></strong> — invokes all handlers registered for that key (string or enum).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log">← <code>log</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-parallel-input-params-schema">ParallelNode · input_params_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · ParallelNode — input_params_schema (ParallelNodeInputParams)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-parallel-input-params-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-event-hook-manager">← Event hook manager</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview">Overview →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · ParallelNode</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>input_params_schema</code> — <code>ParallelNodeInputParams</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        <code>ParallelNode</code> (<code>nos.core.engine.node.parallel_node</code>) is a composite node that runs several workflow child nodes concurrently (thread pool), merges shared-state updates, and returns aggregated <code>NodeOutput</code>.
                        Its <code>input_params_schema</code> property returns the Pydantic model <strong><code>ParallelNodeInputParams</code></strong>.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">class ParallelNodeInputParams(BaseModel):
    node_ids: List[str] = Field(
        default_factory=list,
        description="List of workflow node IDs to run in parallel",
    )
    merge_strategy: MergeStrategy = Field(
        default="last_wins",
        description="last_wins | first_wins | combine | error_on_conflict",
    )
    on_error: OnErrorStrategy = Field(
        default="fail_fast",
        description="fail_fast | continue_on_error",
    )</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Runtime resolution</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>node_ids</code></strong> — taken from <code>input_params</code> when present; otherwise from workflow <code>state</code> keys <code>node_ids</code> or <code>parallel_node_ids</code>. Must be non-empty and must name nodes registered on the same parent workflow.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>merge_strategy</code></strong> — how concurrent state updates are merged into shared workflow state (<code>last_wins</code>, <code>first_wins</code>, <code>combine</code>, <code>error_on_conflict</code>).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>on_error</code></strong> — <code>fail_fast</code> stops on the first failure; <code>continue_on_error</code> collects errors and keeps going where possible.</li>
                            <li><strong>Parent workflow</strong> — <code>ParallelNode</code> requires <code>_workflow</code> to be set (the engine attaches it when the node is part of a workflow). Without it, execution returns an error in metadata.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-event-hook-manager">← Event hook manager</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview">Overview →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — Workflow __init__ (constructor)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-init">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-intro">← Introduction</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-state-schema">state_schema →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>__init__</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Constructor for every <code>Workflow</code> subclass. Plugins usually declare
                        <strong><code>workflow_id</code></strong> (and optionally <strong><code>name</code></strong>) as <strong>class attributes</strong> and call
                        <code>super().__init__()</code> with no arguments. You may pass <code>workflow_id</code> / <code>name</code> explicitly to override those defaults (e.g. tests or dynamic registration).
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def __init__(self, workflow_id: str = None, name: str = None):
    ...</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem">Example — <strong>class attributes</strong> (typical plugin): <code>workflow_id</code> / <code>name</code> on the subclass, then <code>super().__init__()</code> with no arguments.</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">from nos.core.engine.base import Workflow

class MyWorkflow(Workflow):
    workflow_id = "my_wf"
    name = "My workflow"

    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()

    def define(self):
        ...  # add_node, add_link, set_entry_node, …</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem">Example — <strong>explicit <code>workflow_id</code> / <code>name</code></strong> at construction (tests, dynamic id, or overriding the class defaults): pass them into <code>super().__init__(...)</code> or call the constructor with keyword arguments.</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python"># Override at instantiation (subclass still may declare class workflow_id as default)
wf = MyWorkflow(workflow_id="staging_my_wf", name="Staging run")

# Or forward parameters from your own __init__:
class TenantWorkflow(Workflow):
    workflow_id = "tenant_tpl"  # optional default when args omitted

    def __init__(self, tenant_id: str):
        super().__init__(
            workflow_id=f"tenant_{tenant_id}",
            name=f"Tenant {tenant_id}",
        )

    def define(self):
        ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Behaviour</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>workflow_id</code></strong> — If omitted, taken from the subclass class attribute <code>workflow_id</code> (required in that case; otherwise <code>TypeError</code>).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>name</code></strong> — Display label; defaults to the class attribute <code>name</code> if set, else <code>workflow_id</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Internal graph</strong> — Empty <code>_nodes</code>, <code>_links</code>, <code>_entry_node_id</code>; populated when your <code>define()</code> runs (<code>add_node</code>, <code>add_link</code>, …).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>_exec_log</code></strong> — <code>None</code> until the engine attaches a buffer; workflow code uses the public <code>self.exec_log</code> property.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        After construction, the engine (or tests) call <code>define()</code> to register nodes and links.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-intro">← Introduction</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-state-schema">state_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — state_schema (property)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-state-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-init">← <code>__init__</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-output-schema">output_schema →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Properties</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">state_schema</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>Pydantic v2 <code>BaseModel</code></strong> class describing the workflow’s <strong>shared mutable state</strong>.
                        The engine validates initial and evolving state against this model when it is defined; returning <code>None</code> skips structural validation (raw dict).
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def state_schema(self) -&gt; Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>REST / API</strong> — Initial workflow <code>state</code> supplied by execute/run endpoints is validated against this model when defined, before the run starts.</li>
                            <li><strong>CLI / automation</strong> — Console command <code>run workflow …</code> accepts repeatable <code>--state key=value</code>; values merge into the same initial state dict, with field names matching the model attributes.</li>
                            <li><strong>Console &amp; forms</strong> — Interactive and debug workflow runs use this schema to build the <strong>state</strong> section of forms and apply Pydantic defaults (alongside workflow-level params when the UI exposes them).</li>
                            <li><strong>Shared state</strong> — During execution, nodes read and update the same workflow <code>state</code> dict; link routing and <code>StateMapping</code> depend on these keys. The engine can re-validate state after steps when a schema is set.</li>
                            <li><strong>Output validation</strong> — <code>validate_output</code> uses <code>output_schema</code> when set; otherwise it falls back to <code>state_schema</code> for the final data payload.</li>
                            <li><strong>Implement</strong> — Override on your <code>Workflow</code> subclass and return a concrete model (or <code>None</code>).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-init">← <code>__init__</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-output-schema">output_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — output_schema (property)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-output-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-state-schema">← state_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-metadata-schema">metadata_schema →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Properties</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">output_schema</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>Pydantic v2 <code>BaseModel</code></strong> for the workflow <strong>result <code>data</code></strong> — the value stored at <code>WorkflowExecutionResult.response.output["data"]</code> — when that shape should differ from the final shared state (subset, rename, or different structure).
                        If <code>None</code>, <code>validate_output</code> uses <code>state_schema</code>; if both are <code>None</code>, the engine returns data as-is.
                        The renderable contract matches the node: <code>response.output</code> is always <code>{"output_format", "data"}</code>; <code>output_schema</code> applies to <code>data</code> only.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def output_schema(self) -&gt; Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>Result nesting</strong> — mirror of the node: <code>WorkflowOutput</code> is the small <code>output</code> + <code>metadata</code> pair; the engine embeds it in <code>WorkflowExecutionResult.response</code> (<code>WorkflowResponseData</code>), same nesting idea as <code>NodeOutput</code> → <code>NodeExecutionResult.response</code>.</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">from typing import Optional, Type
from pydantic import BaseModel, Field
from nos.core.engine import Workflow, WorkflowExecutionResult, WorkflowOutput, WorkflowResponseData


class MyWorkflowOutput(BaseModel):
    """Validated shape of response.output['data'] when output_schema returns this model."""
    sum_result: float = Field(..., ge=0)


class MyWorkflow(Workflow):
    workflow_id = "my_workflow"

    @property
    def output_schema(self) -&gt; Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
        return MyWorkflowOutput

    def define(self):
        pass  # real workflows: add_node, add_link, set_entry_node


# Engine builds WorkflowOutput then WorkflowExecutionResult:
# wf_piece = WorkflowOutput(
#     output={"output_format": "json", "data": {"sum_result": 5.0}},
#     metadata={"nodes_run": 2},
# )
# WorkflowExecutionResult(
#     execution_id=..., workflow_id="my_workflow", status="success",
#     response=WorkflowResponseData(
#         output=dict(wf_piece.output),   # output_format + data
#         metadata=dict(wf_piece.metadata),
#     ),
#     state=..., initial_state=..., state_changed=..., event_logs=..., ...
# )</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>validate_output</code></strong> — Called with the final state dict before <code>WorkflowExecutionResult</code> is built; chooses <code>output_schema</code> over <code>state_schema</code> when defined; validated value becomes <code>response.output["data"]</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>WorkflowOutput.output["data"]</code></strong> / <strong><code>WorkflowExecutionResult.response.output["data"]</code></strong> — same logical field after the run.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>metadata_schema</code></strong> — validates <code>WorkflowOutput.metadata</code> / <code>response.metadata</code> separately.</li>
                            <li><strong>Typical case</strong> — Leave <code>None</code> when the API response <code>data</code> should match validated workflow state (<code>state_schema</code>).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-state-schema">← state_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-metadata-schema">metadata_schema →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — metadata_schema (property)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-metadata-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-output-schema">← output_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-define">define →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Properties</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">metadata_schema</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>Pydantic v2 <code>BaseModel</code></strong> for the workflow <strong>metadata</strong> dict returned by <code>get_metadata()</code>.
                        The engine validates that dict before assembling <code>WorkflowExecutionResult.response</code> when a schema is set; <code>None</code> keeps metadata as a raw dict.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def metadata_schema(self) -&gt; Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>get_metadata</code></strong> — Override to supply counts, summaries, or run context; base returns <code>{}</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>validate_metadata</code></strong> — Uses <code>metadata_schema</code> when defined (called on success paths in the engine).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-output-schema">← output_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-define">define →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — define (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-define">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-metadata-schema">← metadata_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node">add_node →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>define</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Abstract method you implement on every <code>Workflow</code> subclass to <strong>declare the graph</strong>:
                        register nodes, links, and the entry node.
                        The engine does not call <code>define()</code> directly from outside your class; <code>prepare()</code> invokes it before state initialization.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@abstractmethod
def define(self):
    """
    Define workflow structure.

    This method should:
    - Create nodes using self.add_node()
    - Create links using self.add_link()
    - Set entry node using self.set_entry_node()
    """
    pass</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Behaviour</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>prepare()</code></strong> — Calls <code>define()</code> then <code>initialize_state</code>; callers should use <code>prepare</code> / engine entry points rather than calling <code>define()</code> alone.</li>
                            <li><strong>Order</strong> — Typical pattern: <code>add_node</code> for each step, <code>add_link</code> for routing, then <code>set_entry_node</code> so execution has a valid starting <code>node_id</code>.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-metadata-schema">← metadata_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node">add_node →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — add_node (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-add-node">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-define">← define</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node-workflow">add_node_workflow →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>add_node</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Registers a <code>Node</code> instance on the workflow graph. Call from <code>define()</code> for each step.
                        Optional <code>state_mapping</code> overrides how the node reads/writes shared workflow state.
                        Optional <code>default_input_params</code> holds only parameters that belong to the node’s
                        <code>input_params_schema</code> (timeouts, limits, …): they are stored per <code>node_id</code> and supplied
                        on <strong>every</strong> run when the engine calls <code>node.run()</code>. The workflow’s
                        <code>output_format</code> is passed separately as <code>output_format=…</code> (see Behaviour).
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def add_node(
    self,
    node: Node,
    state_mapping: Optional[StateMapping] = None,
    *,
    default_input_params: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None,
) -&gt; None:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Behaviour</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Storage</strong> — Node is stored under <code>node.node_id</code>; the node receives <code>node._workflow = self</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>default_input_params</code> (node parameters)</strong> — Saved at <code>add_node</code> time and merged into the <code>input_params</code> value passed to <code>node.run()</code> on each workflow step. Those keys are what <code>Node._on_init</code> validates against <code>input_params_schema</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>output_format</code> (workflow run)</strong> — Comes from <code>Workflow.run(..., output_format=…)</code> (or the engine). The workflow step calls <code>node.run(..., output_format=…)</code> as a <strong>keyword argument</strong>, not inside <code>default_input_params</code>. It is not read from the <code>input_params</code> dict for rendering (a schema field named <code>output_format</code>, if you define one, is domain data only).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-define">← define</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node-workflow">add_node_workflow →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — add_node_workflow (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-add-node-workflow">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node">← add_node</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-link">add_link →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>add_node_workflow</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Adds a <strong>child workflow</strong> as a single node step: builds a <code>NodeWorkflow</code>, then calls
                        <code>add_node</code>. The child receives parent state as <code>initial_state</code>; its output is merged back like any node.
                        Resolution uses the registry first, then optional <code>module_path</code> + <code>class_name</code>.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def add_node_workflow(
    self,
    workflow_id: str,
    node_id: Optional[str] = None,
    name: Optional[str] = None,
    module_path: Optional[str] = None,
    class_name: Optional[str] = None,
    state_mapping: Optional[StateMapping] = None,
) -&gt; str:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Returns</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>str</code></strong> — The new node’s <code>node_id</code> (for <code>add_link</code>, <code>set_entry_node</code>).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node">← add_node</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-link">add_link →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — add_link (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-add-link">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node-workflow">← add_node_workflow</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-set-entry-node">set_entry_node →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>add_link</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Registers a <code>Link</code> on the workflow (routing between nodes). Call from <code>define()</code> after the
                        referenced nodes exist. If the workflow has an <code>exec_log</code>, it is attached to the link.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def add_link(self, link: Link) -&gt; None:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-node-workflow">← add_node_workflow</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-set-entry-node">set_entry_node →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — set_entry_node (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-set-entry-node">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-link">← add_link</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-load">load →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>set_entry_node</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Declares which node the workflow runs <strong>first</strong>. Call it from <code>define()</code> after
                        <code>add_node</code> has registered <code>node_id</code>. The engine starts execution from this node and follows
                        outgoing links (including <code>ChainLink</code> hop-by-hop) from there.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def set_entry_node(self, node_id: str) -&gt; None:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Behaviour</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>node_id</code></strong> — Must already exist in <code>self._nodes</code>; otherwise <code>ValueError</code> (“Entry node … not found”).</li>
                            <li><strong>Effect</strong> — Sets <code>_entry_node_id</code>. If it stays unset, the engine raises <code>ValueError</code> (“has no entry node”) when execution starts — call <code>set_entry_node</code> from <code>define()</code> after registering nodes.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem">Example — inside <code>define()</code>:</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def define(self):
    self.add_node(self._sum_node)
    self.add_node(self._dot_node)
    self.add_link(AlwaysLink(...))
    self.set_entry_node("sum")</code></pre>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-add-link">← add_link</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-load">load →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — load (classmethod)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-load">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-set-entry-node">← set_entry_node</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run">run →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>load</code> <span style="font-weight:500;font-size:0.85em">(classmethod)</span></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Resolve a workflow instance from the in-memory <strong>registry</strong> (<code>prod</code>) or by importing a Python module (<code>dev</code>).
                        The returned object stores <code>_load_spec</code> so a later <code>run(background=True)</code> can replay the same resolution through <code>WorkflowEngine</code>.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@classmethod
def load(
    cls,
    mode: Literal["dev", "prod"],
    workflow_id: str,
    *,
    module_path: Optional[str] = None,
    class_name: Optional[str] = None,
    **kwargs: Any,
) -&gt; "Workflow":
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Rules</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>prod</code></strong> — <code>workflow_registry.create_workflow_instance(workflow_id)</code>; <code>module_path</code> / <code>class_name</code> are ignored (warning if set).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>dev</code></strong> — Requires <code>module_path</code> and <code>class_name</code>; imports the class and instantiates it with <code>workflow_id=…</code> plus <code>**kwargs</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Typing</strong> — The loaded class must be a subclass of the <code>cls</code> you call <code>load</code> on (usually <code>Workflow</code>).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem">Example — dev module load then synchronous <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run" href="#"><code>run</code></a>:</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">wf = Workflow.load(
    "dev",
    "my_wf_id",
    module_path="nos.plugins.workflows.example.my_wf",
    class_name="MyWorkflow",
)
result = wf.run(initial_state={}, debug_mode="trace")</code></pre>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-set-entry-node">← set_entry_node</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run">run →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — run (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-run">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-load">← load</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks">EventLogBuffer / EventLog →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>run</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        <strong>High-level entry point</strong> for executing a workflow from Python without wiring your own
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks" href="#"><code>EventLogBuffer</code> / Socket.IO channel</a>. It delegates to the shared
                        <code>WorkflowEngine.execute_sync</code> with <code>exec_log=None</code> (the engine creates an in-memory buffer).
                        For interactive forms, realtime logs, or REST-style channels, call
                        <code>get_shared_engine().execute_sync(workflow, exec_log=…, request=…)</code> or
                        <code>execute_background(..., request=…)</code> instead—the same <code>request</code> semantics apply.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def run(
    self,
    initial_state: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None,
    *,
    output_format: str = "json",
    request: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None,
    background: bool = False,
    callback: Optional[Callable[[Dict[str, Any]], None]] = None,
    debug_mode: Literal["trace", "debug"] = "trace",
    exec_log: Any = None,
) -&gt; Union[WorkflowExecutionResult, str]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Parameters &amp; <code>request</code></span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>initial_state</code></strong> — Optional dict passed to <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-on-start" href="#"><code>_on_start(initial_state)</code></a> and then to <code>prepare(initial_state)</code> (same reference). The engine calls <code>_on_start</code> <strong>before</strong> <code>prepare</code> / <code>define</code> / shared-state validation, so you can mutate it in place in <code>_on_start</code> to build dynamic shared state—see <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-on-start" href="#">Workflow <code>_on_start</code></a>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>output_format</code></strong> — Render format for <code>WorkflowExecutionResult.response.output</code> (e.g. <code>json</code>, <code>text</code>). Distinct from <code>debug_mode</code> (trace vs interactive node forms).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>debug_mode</code></strong> — <code>"trace"</code> or <code>"debug"</code>; forwarded to <code>WorkflowEngine.execute_sync</code> / <code>execute_background</code> to control per-node interactive forms on platform logs.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>background</code></strong> — If <code>True</code>, returns an <code>execution_id</code> string from <code>execute_background</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>exec_log</code></strong> — Optional buffer or platform log; <code>None</code> lets the engine create a default in-memory buffer.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>request</code></strong> — Optional <strong>workflow-level caller context</strong> (API/CLI tracing, <code>tenant_id</code>, etc.). The engine keeps a shallow copy for the duration of the run and exposes it to every node step under <strong><code>workflow_run_request</code></strong> — see <em>How <code>request</code> reaches each node</em> below. The same dict is used to populate <code>WorkflowExecutionResult.command</code> when you set a string <code>"command"</code> key.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>command</code></strong> — If <code>request</code> contains <code>"command"</code> as a string, <code>WorkflowExecutionResult.command</code> is set to that value (echo of the invoking command or operation name).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p style="font-size:0.88rem;line-height:1.72;margin:0.85rem 0 0">
                        <strong>Dynamic shared state.</strong> Pass a mutable dict as <code>initial_state</code>; the engine invokes <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-on-start" href="#"><code>_on_start</code></a> on that same object before <code>prepare</code>, so you can fill or adjust keys synchronously (e.g. config fetch) before <code>state_schema</code> validation. Example patterns: <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-on-start" href="#">Workflow <code>_on_start</code></a>.
                    </p>

                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>How <code>request</code> reaches each node</strong></p>
                    <p>
                        <code>Workflow.run</code>, <code>WorkflowEngine.execute_sync</code>, and <code>execute_background</code> follow the same rule:
                        if <code>request</code> is a dict, the engine assigns a <strong>shallow copy</strong> to the workflow for the lifetime of that run
                        (internal attribute used only during execution). For <strong>each node step</strong>, the engine calls:
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">node.run(
    observable_state,   # mapped workflow state for this node
    input_params,       # merged default_input_params for this node_id
    request={
        "node_id": ...,
        "workflow_id": ...,
        "state": ...,           # snapshot for this step
        "input_params": ...,
        "output_format": ...,   # same as the keyword below (for tracing)
        "workflow_run_request": &lt;your workflow request dict or None&gt;,
        "workflow_engine_debug_mode": "trace" | "debug",
    },
    output_format=...,   # from Workflow.run / engine; not part of input_params_schema
)</code></pre>
                    <ul class="nos-api-assoc" style="margin-top:0.35rem">
                        <li><strong>Your keys</strong> (<code>tenant_id</code>, <code>user_id</code>, <code>command</code>, …) appear under <strong><code>workflow_run_request</code></strong>, not at the top level of the node’s <code>request</code>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Engine keys</strong> (<code>node_id</code>, <code>workflow_id</code>, <code>state</code>, <code>input_params</code> for the step) are <strong>siblings</strong> at the top level—so the node can see both graph context and original caller context in one dict.</li>
                        <li><strong>Direct <code>node.run(...)</code></strong> from Python without the workflow engine does <strong>not</strong> use this envelope; see <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run" href="#"><code>Node.run</code></a> for standalone <code>request</code>.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem">Example — start a workflow with context; read it from a node’s <code>_on_start</code> (stash on <code>self</code> if <code>_do_execute</code> needs it):</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">result = wf.run(
    initial_state={"doc_id": "42"},
    request={
        "command": "run workflow ingest --tenant acme",
        "tenant_id": "acme",
        "user_id": "u7",
    },
)
assert result.command == "run workflow ingest --tenant acme"

# With a custom exec_log (Socket.IO / REST channel):
# get_shared_engine().execute_sync(
#     wf, initial_state={...}, exec_log=channel, request={...}, debug_mode="debug",
# )</code></pre>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_start(self, request: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; Optional[bool]:
    super()._on_start(request)
    wf_ctx = (request or {}).get("workflow_run_request") or {}
    self._tenant_id = wf_ctx.get("tenant_id")
    self._user_id = wf_ctx.get("user_id")
    # Top-level request also has node_id, workflow_id, state, input_params for this step
    return True</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>Propagating <code>ctx_wf</code> inside the node (<code>_on_start</code> → <code>_do_execute</code>)</strong></p>
                    <p>
                        The engine passes workflow caller context only through the <code>request</code> argument of <code>node.run</code>.
                        <code>execute()</code> / <code>_do_execute</code> do <strong>not</strong> receive that dict—so the usual pattern is: read
                        <code>ctx_wf = (request or {}).get("workflow_run_request") or {}</code> in <code>_on_start</code>, then copy the fields you need onto
                        <code>self</code> (or keep the whole dict on <code>self._wf_ctx</code>). The same node instance is used for that step only until
                        <code>run()</code> returns; the next workflow step calls <code>run()</code> again and <code>_on_start</code> runs again with a fresh envelope
                        (same <code>workflow_run_request</code> reference for every step of one workflow run).
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">from typing import Any, Dict, Optional

from nos.core.engine.base import Node, NodeOutput


class IngestNode(Node):
    """Workflow caller request=… is nested as workflow_run_request on each node.run envelope."""

    def _on_start(self, request: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; Optional[bool]:
        super()._on_start(request)
        ctx_wf = (request or {}).get("workflow_run_request") or {}
        # Propagate into the body of the run (visible in _do_execute)
        self._wf_ctx = ctx_wf
        self._wf_step_node_id = (request or {}).get("node_id")
        return True

    def _do_execute(self, state_dict: Dict[str, Any], params_dict: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; NodeOutput:
        tenant = (getattr(self, "_wf_ctx", None) or {}).get("tenant_id")
        user = (getattr(self, "_wf_ctx", None) or {}).get("user_id")
        # ... use tenant / user for I/O, logging, headers, etc.
        return NodeOutput(
            output={
                "output_format": "json",
                "data": {"ok": True, "tenant": tenant, "user": user, "doc_id": state_dict.get("doc_id")},
            }
        )</code></pre>
                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.5rem 0 0">Chain summary: <code>wf.run(..., request=ctx)</code> → engine stores <code>ctx</code> on the workflow → each step <code>node.run(..., request=…)</code> includes <code>workflow_run_request=ctx</code> → <code>_on_start</code> assigns <code>ctx_wf</code> → stash on <code>self</code> → <code>_do_execute</code> reads <code>self._wf_ctx</code>.</p>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        Use JSON-friendly values in <code>request</code>; agree on key names between workflow callers and node implementations.
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run" href="#"><code>Node.run</code></a> documents the simpler standalone case where <em>you</em> pass <code>request</code> and there is no <code>workflow_run_request</code> wrapper.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-set-entry-node">← set_entry_node</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-on-start">Workflow <code>_on_start</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Workflow — _on_start (lifecycle)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-workflow-on-start">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run">← <code>run</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks">EventLogBuffer / EventLog →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Workflow · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_start</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Called by <code>WorkflowEngine</code> <strong>after</strong> <code>set_exec_log</code> (so <code>self.exec_log</code> and the scoped hook bus exist, same idea as nodes) and <strong>before</strong>
                        <code>prepare()</code> — i.e. <strong>before</strong> <code>define()</code>, shared-state validation (<code>_initialize_state</code>), and <code>_on_init</code> telemetry.
                        This mirrors <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start" href="#"><code>Node._on_start</code></a> running before <code>execute()</code> / <code>_on_init</code>.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_start(self, initial_state: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None) -&gt; None:
    ...</code></pre>
                    <p>
                        The <code>initial_state</code> argument is the <strong>same dict reference</strong> the engine will pass to <code>prepare(initial_state)</code> next.
                        You can <strong>mutate that dict in place</strong> (e.g. fill it after a synchronous HTTP call) so <code>prepare</code> sees the updated keys before schema validation.
                    </p>
                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>Engine order (sync / background)</strong></p>
                    <ol style="font-size:0.88rem;line-height:1.72;margin:0.35rem 0 0 1.1rem">
                        <li><code>workflow.set_exec_log(exec_log)</code></li>
                        <li><code>workflow._on_start(initial_state)</code></li>
                        <li><code>workflow.prepare(initial_state)</code> → <code>define</code> + <code>_initialize_state</code> + <code>_on_init</code></li>
                        <li>Optional initial-state form (platform log), then graph execution</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>Example — dynamic shared state before validation</strong></p>
                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0 0 0.35rem">Build one mutable dict, pass it to <code>run</code>; override <code>_on_start</code> to fetch and update in place (use sync HTTP; the hook is synchronous):</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">import urllib.request
import json
from typing import Any, Dict, Optional

from nos.core.engine.workflow.workflow import Workflow


class FetchConfigWorkflow(Workflow):
    workflow_id = "fetch_config_example"

    def _on_start(self, initial_state: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None) -&gt; None:
        super()._on_start(initial_state)
        st = initial_state if initial_state is not None else {}
        # Example: fill defaults from a remote config before prepare() validates state_schema
        try:
            with urllib.request.urlopen("https://httpbin.org/json", timeout=5) as resp:
                payload = json.loads(resp.read().decode())
            st.setdefault("slideshow", payload.get("slideshow", {}))
        except Exception as exc:
            self.exec_log.log("warning", f"fetch skipped: {exc}", event="wf_prefetch")

    def define(self) -&gt; None:
        ...  # add_node, add_link, set_entry_node as usual</code></pre>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python"># Caller: same dict object is passed to _on_start and prepare
seed: Dict[str, Any] = {}
result = wf.run(initial_state=seed, debug_mode="trace")
# seed may now contain keys added in _on_start before schema validation</code></pre>
                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0.85rem">
                        <strong>Workflow vs node.</strong> For a <strong>node</strong>, mutate <code>state</code> / <code>input_params</code> in <code>_on_start</code> before <code>_on_init</code>
                        (<a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run-dynamic" href="#">Node.run — dynamic state</a>).
                        For a <strong>workflow</strong>, mutate the <strong>same</strong> <code>initial_state</code> dict here before <code>prepare</code>.
                    </p>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run">← <code>run</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-event-log-sinks">EventLogBuffer / EventLog →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Event handling — Lifecycle _on_start
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview">← Overview</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-init"><code>_on_init</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_start</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Called from <code>run()</code> <strong>before</strong> <code>execute()</code> — so <strong>before initialization</strong> (<code>_on_init</code>, schema validation, and the rest of the execution pipeline). The <code>request</code> argument is whatever the caller passed to <code>run(..., request=…)</code>, or a minimal dict of normalised <code>state</code> / <code>input_params</code> when <code>request</code> was omitted (<a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run" href="#"><code>Node.run</code></a>).
                        When the node runs as a <strong>workflow step</strong>, the engine supplies a larger envelope and nests workflow-level context under <strong><code>workflow_run_request</code></strong> (<a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run" href="#"><code>Workflow.run</code></a>).
                        The base implementation emits <strong><code>node_start</code></strong> on the execution log. Return exactly <code>True</code> to continue; any other return value cancels the run (no <code>execute()</code>) with a <code>cancelled</code> result.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_start(self, request: Dict[str, Any]) -> Optional[bool]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.75rem 0 0.35rem">Example — read fields from <code>request</code> before init (<code>WorkflowEngine.run_node</code> often adds <code>execution_id</code>, <code>command</code>, <code>mode</code> at the top level; standalone <code>node.run</code> uses only the keys you passed; workflow steps nest caller context under <code>workflow_run_request</code> — see <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run" href="#"><code>Workflow.run</code></a>):</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_start(self, request: Dict[str, Any]) -> Optional[bool]:
    super()._on_start(request)

    execution_id = request.get("execution_id") or ""
    command = (request.get("command") or "").strip()
    if execution_id:
        # Correlate logs / metrics with the engine run
        logger.info("[%s] %s starting (command=%r)", execution_id, self.node_id, command)

    # Gate before validation: inspect the raw envelope (not yet schema-validated)
    state = request.get("state") or {}
    if state.get("maintenance"):
        if self._exec_log:
            self._exec_log.log(
                "warning",
                "Execution rejected: maintenance flag on workflow state",
                event="rejected_maintenance",
            )
        return False

    if command.startswith("dry-run"):
        if self._exec_log:
            self._exec_log.log(
                "info",
                "Dry-run prefix detected on command; downstream logic may skip writes",
                event="dry_run_hint",
                command=command,
            )

    return True</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.88rem;line-height:1.72;margin:0.85rem 0 0">
                        When <code>run()</code> builds the default <code>request</code> (you did not pass one), <code>request["state"]</code> and <code>request["input_params"]</code> reference the <strong>same dicts</strong> as the <code>state</code> and <code>input_params</code> arguments to <code>run()</code>—so in-place updates here are what <code>_on_init</code> validates. See <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run-dynamic" href="#">Node.run — dynamic state</a>.
                    </p>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">Always call <code>super()._on_start(request)</code> when overriding so the standard <code>node_start</code> event is still emitted.</p>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview">← Overview</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-init"><code>_on_init</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-init">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start">← <code>_on_start</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-state-changed"><code>_on_state_changed</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_init</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Start of <code>execute()</code>: validates <code>state</code> and <code>input_params</code> against schemas, validates the <code>requested_output_format</code> passed into <code>execute()</code> (from <code>Node.run(..., output_format=…)</code> / engine), checks key collisions, and returns an <code>_InitResult</code> with validated dicts and timestamps. The base implementation emits <strong><code>node_init</code></strong> before validation and <strong><code>node_init_completed</code></strong> after success.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_init(
    self,
    state: Dict[str, Any],
    input_params: Any,
    *,
    requested_output_format: Optional[str] = None,
) -> _InitResult:
    ...</code></pre>
                    <p class="nos-api-note">Override to wrap pre/post logic around <code>super()._on_init(...)</code>; validation failures map to <code>validation_error</code> results and <code>_on_error</code> when an execution log is attached.</p>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start">← <code>_on_start</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-state-changed"><code>_on_state_changed</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-state-changed">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-init">← <code>_on_init</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-input"><code>_on_input</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_state_changed</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Invoked whenever workflow state is mutated through an <code>ObservableStateDict</code> callback (each <code>state[key] = value</code>). The base implementation emits <strong><code>node_state_changed</code></strong> with <code>key</code>, <code>old_value</code>, and <code>new_value</code> for traceability across the run.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_state_changed(self, key: str, old_value: Any, new_value: Any) -> None:
    ...</code></pre>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-init">← <code>_on_init</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-input"><code>_on_input</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-input">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-state-changed">← <code>_on_state_changed</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-end"><code>_on_end</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_input</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Called when the interactive debug form returns (after <code>request_and_wait</code>). The base implementation emits <strong><code>node_form_response_received</code></strong>. Use it to log or react to user-edited state/parameters before execution continues.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_input(self, form_response: Dict[str, Any]) -> None:
    ...</code></pre>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-state-changed">← <code>_on_state_changed</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-end"><code>_on_end</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-end">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-input">← <code>_on_input</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-error"><code>_on_error</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_end</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Terminal hook for <strong>every</strong> finished run: success, cancellation, or (after <code>_on_error</code>) failure. The base implementation emits <strong><code>node_end</code></strong> with the final <code>NodeExecutionResult</code> and a log level/message (e.g. <code>warning</code> for cooperative cancel).
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_end(
    self,
    result: NodeExecutionResult,
    level: str = "info",
    message: str = "Node execution completed",
) -> None:
    ...</code></pre>
                    <p class="nos-api-note">On error paths the framework usually calls <code>_on_error</code> first, which then delegates to <code>_on_end</code> with <code>level="error"</code>.</p>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-input">← <code>_on_input</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-error"><code>_on_error</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-error">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-end">← <code>_on_end</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-stop"><code>_on_stop</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_error</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Invoked when <code>execute()</code> (or early <code>run()</code> paths) builds an <strong>error</strong> <code>NodeExecutionResult</code>: e.g. validation failure after init, an exception inside <code>_do_execute</code>, invalid return from <code>_do_execute</code>, or output/metadata validation failure. The base implementation emits <strong><code>node_error</code></strong>, then calls <code>_on_end(result, level="error", …)</code> so observers always see a closing <code>node_end</code> with a consistent payload.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_error(self, result: NodeExecutionResult) -> None:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <p style="margin-top:0.85rem;font-weight:600;color:var(--fx-text);line-height:1.55">
                        Inside <code>_do_execute</code>, you must follow <strong>only these two supported options</strong> when something goes wrong. Do <strong>not</strong> call <code>_on_error</code> yourself from plugin code.
                    </p>
                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Required patterns in <code>_do_execute</code></span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Option 1 — Propagate the exception (<code>raise</code>)</strong> — Do not catch, or catch only to log / wrap, then <strong>re-raise</strong> (<code>raise</code> or <code>raise … from e</code>). The framework catches it (except <code>CancellationError</code>, which is handled separately), builds an error <code>NodeExecutionResult</code>, fills <code>event_logs</code>, and invokes <strong><code>_on_error(result)</code></strong> for you. This is the correct path for technical failures (<code>internal_error</code>, etc.).</li>
                            <li><strong>Option 2 — Recover and return <code>NodeOutput</code></strong> — If the situation is a <strong>business-level</strong> outcome that should still count as a <strong>completed</strong> run, handle it in <code>try</code>/<code>except</code> (or normal control flow) and <strong>return</strong> a valid <code>NodeOutput</code> whose <code>data</code> describes the outcome (e.g. <code>{"ok": false, "reason": "…"}</code>). The framework then follows the success path and calls <code>_on_end</code> with <code>status="completed"</code>; <code>_on_error</code> is <strong>not</strong> used for that run.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0.65rem">
                        <strong>Not supported:</strong> calling <code>self._on_error(...)</code> from inside <code>_do_execute</code>. That hook is driven by <code>execute()</code> with a fully built result; doing it manually can duplicate <code>node_end</code> / corrupt the lifecycle. Stick to <strong>Option 1</strong> or <strong>Option 2</strong> only.
                    </p>
                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">When the framework calls <code>_on_error</code></span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Teardown order</strong> — <code>_on_error</code> emits <code>node_error</code>, then calls <code>_on_end(result, level="error", …)</code> so clients always see a terminal <code>node_end</code> after errors.</li>
                            <li><strong>Triggers</strong> — Besides exceptions from <code>_do_execute</code> (Option 1), the framework also calls <code>_on_error</code> for validation failures after init, invalid return type from <code>_do_execute</code>, output/metadata validation errors, and similar paths.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <p class="nos-api-note">Override <code>_on_error</code> on your subclass for extra logging or metrics; call <code>super()._on_error(result)</code> so <code>node_error</code> and the terminal <code>node_end</code> still fire.</p>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-end">← <code>_on_end</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-stop"><code>_on_stop</code> →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-stop">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-error">← <code>_on_error</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log">Event log →</a>
                    </nav>
                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Event handling · Lifecycle</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_on_stop</code></h2>
                    </header>
                    <p>
                        Invoked when the user or engine requests <strong>cooperative cancellation</strong>: the next
                        <code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code> / <code>log_custom</code> raises <code>CancellationError</code>,
                        <code>execute()</code> builds a <code>NodeExecutionResult</code> with <code>status="cancelled"</code>, then calls
                        <strong><code>_on_stop</code></strong> (only when an execution log is attached). The base implementation emits
                        <strong><code>node.stop</code></strong> on the scoped run bus (adapter → <code>log_node_stop</code>), then
                        <code>_on_end(result, level="warning", …)</code> so clients still receive a full terminal <code>node_end</code>.
                        <strong><code>_on_error</code> is not used</strong> for this path.
                    </p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_stop(
    self,
    result: NodeExecutionResult,
    message: str = "Execution cancelled by user",
) -&gt; None:
    ...</code></pre>
                    <p style="margin-top:0.85rem;font-weight:600;color:var(--fx-text);line-height:1.55">
                        Extend with teardown or metrics — always finish with <code>super()._on_stop(...)</code> unless you intentionally replace telemetry.
                    </p>
                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Example — release resources on cancel</span>
                        </div>
                        <pre class="nos-api-signature" style="margin:0.5rem 0.65rem 0.85rem;border-radius:8px"><code class="language-python">from typing import Any

class MyNode(Node):
    def __init__(self, *args: Any, **kwargs: Any):
        super().__init__(*args, **kwargs)
        self._external_handle = None  # e.g. client, temp dir, pool

    def _on_stop(self, result: NodeExecutionResult, message: str = "Execution cancelled by user") -&gt; None:
        try:
            if self._external_handle is not None:
                self._external_handle.close()
                self._external_handle = None
        finally:
            super()._on_stop(result, message)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <p class="nos-api-note">Do not call <code>_on_stop</code> from <code>_do_execute</code>; it is driven by <code>execute()</code> after a cooperative cancel, like <code>_on_error</code> for failures.</p>
                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-error">← <code>_on_error</code></a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log">Event log →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — metadata_schema (in-page reference)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-metadata-schema">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log">← exec_log</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-allowed-output-formats">ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">metadata_schema</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>Pydantic v2 <code>BaseModel</code></strong> describing the shape of <code>NodeOutput.metadata</code>.
                        After <code>_do_execute</code>, the engine validates <code>metadata</code> with this model when it is defined; returning <code>None</code> keeps metadata as an unconstrained dict.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def metadata_schema(self) -> Optional[Type[BaseModel]]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>NodeOutput.metadata</code></strong> — supplementary fields (timing, provenance, debug stats, etc.) returned alongside <code>output</code>; validated and coerced to a plain dict when a schema is set.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>output_schema</code></strong> — validates <code>output["data"]</code> only; metadata is a separate contract — use both when you want typed primary payload and typed sidecar metadata.</li>
                            <li><strong>Responses</strong> — <code>NodeExecutionResult.response.metadata</code> carries the validated dict to API, CLI and console consumers.</li>
                            <li><strong>Validation errors</strong> — if metadata (or output data, when <code>output_schema</code> applies) fails validation, the run ends with <code>status="output_validation_error"</code> and structured error detail in the response.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log">← exec_log</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-allowed-output-formats">ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API — ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS (in-page reference)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-allowed-output-formats">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-metadata-schema">← metadata_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-do-execute">_do_execute →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        <strong>Class attribute</strong> on <code>Node</code> (not a <code>@property</code>). Restricts which
                        <code>output_format</code> values callers may request for this node. The instance method
                        <code>allowed_output_formats()</code> returns the effective list used by the engine.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python"># On Node base class:
ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS: list = None  # None → all formats in NODE_OUTPUT_FORMATS

# In a subclass (example):
ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS = ["json", "table"]</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Associations</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>allowed_output_formats()</strong> — returns <code>list(self.ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS)</code> when set, otherwise a copy of <code>NODE_OUTPUT_FORMATS</code> from <code>output_formats_schema</code> (e.g. <code>json</code>, <code>text</code>, <code>html</code>, <code>table</code>, <code>code</code>, <code>tree</code>, <code>chart</code>, <code>download</code>).</li>
                            <li><strong>CLI / automation</strong> — Web CLI <code>--output_format</code> and REST <code>output_format</code> (execute body) / <code>Node.run(..., output_format=…)</code> are validated in <code>_on_init</code> against this list; invalid values raise before <code>_do_execute</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Resolution order</strong> — effective render format is still resolved later as CLI &gt; node runtime &gt; <code>default_output_format</code>; <code>ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS</code> only bounds what may be requested.</li>
                            <li><strong>default_output_format</strong> — separate <code>@property</code> for the fallback when the caller does not specify a format; must be one of the allowed formats.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        Set the attribute on the <strong>subclass body</strong> (same style as other class-level node configuration). Use <code>None</code> to allow every built-in format without maintaining a list.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-metadata-schema">← metadata_schema</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-do-execute">_do_execute →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Node — _do_execute (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-do-execute">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-allowed-output-formats">← ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-load">load →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>_do_execute</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        <strong>Abstract hook</strong> you implement on every concrete node subclass. The framework calls it from
                        <code>execute()</code> only after state and parameters are validated, optional debug / form flows complete,
                        and the execution log is ready—your code returns a <code>NodeOutput</code>; the base class then validates
                        <code>output</code> / <code>metadata</code> against <code>output_schema</code> and <code>metadata_schema</code>,
                        resolves <code>output_format</code>, and builds the final <code>NodeExecutionResult</code>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        The leading underscore is a <strong>convention</strong>: this is the extension point for node logic, not the
                        public entry point for runners (use <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-load" href="#"><code>load</code></a> then <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run" href="#"><code>run()</code></a>).
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@abstractmethod
def _do_execute(
    self,
    state_dict: Dict[str, Any],
    params_dict: Dict[str, Any],
) -> NodeOutput:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Inputs &amp; rules</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>state_dict</code></strong> — Validated workflow / context state (<code>input_state_schema</code>). May be an <code>ObservableStateDict</code> when the engine tracks mutations.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>params_dict</code></strong> — Validated input parameters (<code>input_params_schema</code>). Treat as <strong>read-only</strong>; do not mutate.</li>
                            <li><strong>Return</strong> — Always a <code>NodeOutput</code> with <code>output</code> (and optional <code>metadata</code>). Shapes must match your declared schemas and chosen <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-output-formats" href="#">output format</a>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Side effects</strong> — Use <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log" href="#"><code>self.exec_log</code></a> / <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log" href="#"><code>log</code></a> for custom execution-log lines; use <code>request_and_wait</code> / <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-form-input" href="#"><code>request_form_input</code></a> when you need client interaction.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        If <code>_do_execute</code> raises, the framework maps the outcome to the appropriate result status; cooperative
                        cancellation uses <code>CancellationError</code>. Returning a non-<code>NodeOutput</code> value is treated as an
                        internal error.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-allowed-output-formats">← ALLOWED_OUTPUT_FORMATS</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-load">load →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Node — load (classmethod)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-load">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-do-execute">← _do_execute</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run">run() →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>load</code> <span style="font-weight:500;font-size:0.85em">(classmethod)</span></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Resolve a node instance from the registry (<code>prod</code>) or from a Python module (<code>dev</code>).
                        Sets <code>_load_spec</code> on the instance so <code>run(background=True)</code> delegates to <code>WorkflowEngine.run_node</code> with the same <code>mode</code>, <code>module_path</code>, and <code>class_name</code>.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@classmethod
def load(
    cls,
    mode: Literal["dev", "prod"],
    node_id: str,
    *,
    module_path: Optional[str] = None,
    class_name: Optional[str] = None,
    **kwargs: Any,
) -&gt; "Node":
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Rules</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>prod</code></strong> — Registry lookup by <code>node_id</code>; <code>module_path</code> / <code>class_name</code> ignored (warning if set).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>dev</code></strong> — Requires <code>module_path</code> and <code>class_name</code>; constructor receives <code>node_id</code> and <code>**kwargs</code>.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.85rem 0 0.35rem">Then call <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run" href="#"><code>run()</code></a> (sync or background).</p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-do-execute">← _do_execute</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run">run() →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Node — run() (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-run">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-load">← load</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-form-input">request_form_input →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title">run</h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        <strong>Primary entry point</strong> for executing a node. From <strong>plain Python</strong> (tests, scripts, notebooks)
                        you call <code>node.run(state, input_params, request=…)</code> on an instance. The workflow engine, REST layer, and console
                        call the same method for you when you do not invoke the node directly.
                        <code>run()</code> runs the <strong>full outer lifecycle</strong>: optional <code>node_run</code> on the execution log,
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start" href="#"><code>_on_start</code></a> (and <code>node_start</code>),
                        then <code>execute(state, input_params)</code> (validation, optional debug form,
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-do-execute" href="#"><code>_do_execute</code></a>, output validation, terminal hooks).
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Calling <code>execute()</code> directly skips <code>log_node_run</code> and <code>_on_start</code>; use that only when you
                        intentionally bypass the pre-init phase (e.g. narrow tests). Prefer <code>run()</code> whenever you want hooks and a consistent envelope.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def run(
    self,
    state: Dict[str, Any],
    input_params: Any = None,
    request: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None,
    *,
    background: bool = False,
    room: Optional[str] = None,
    callback: Optional[Callable[[Dict[str, Any]], None]] = None,
    persist_to_db: bool = True,
    debug_mode: str = "debug",
    command: Optional[str] = None,
    user_id: str = "anonymous",
    exec_log: Any = None,
    output_format: Optional[str] = None,
) -&gt; Union[NodeExecutionResult, str]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Parameters &amp; behaviour</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>state</code></strong> — Context state (validated against <code>input_state_schema</code> inside <code>execute</code>).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>input_params</code></strong> — Node parameters (validated against <code>input_params_schema</code>). May be a dict or a model.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>debug_mode</code></strong> — <code>"trace"</code> or <code>"debug"</code> for standalone runs: controls the automatic pre-<code>_do_execute</code> form when the sink supports <code>request_and_wait</code>. Not the same as <code>output_format</code> (rendering). When the workflow engine runs the node, it passes <code>workflow_engine_debug_mode</code> inside <code>request</code> instead.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>background</code></strong> — If <code>True</code>, submits via <code>WorkflowEngine.run_node</code> (see <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-load" href="#"><code>load</code></a> for <code>_load_spec</code>).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>exec_log</code></strong> / <strong><code>output_format</code></strong> — Optional; sync path only. If no log is attached, an in-memory buffer is created for the run.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>request</code></strong> — Optional <strong>caller-supplied</strong> dict for anything that is <em>not</em> state or params:
                                correlation ids, test labels, feature flags, dry-run hints, etc. It is passed to
                                <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start" href="#"><code>_on_start(request)</code></a>
                                <strong>unchanged</strong> when you provide it—the framework does <strong>not</strong> merge in <code>state</code>/<code>input_params</code> into your dict.
                                If <code>request</code> is <code>None</code>, <code>run()</code> builds a minimal envelope containing only normalised
                                <code>state</code> and <code>input_params</code> for <code>_on_start</code>.
                                <code>log_node_run</code> sees the same raw <code>request</code> argument you passed to <code>run()</code> (possibly <code>None</code>).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>_on_start</code></strong> — Must return exactly <code>True</code> to continue; any other value yields <code>cancelled</code> without <code>execute()</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Return value</strong> — A complete <code>NodeExecutionResult</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong>Workflow runs</strong> — When the node is executed <em>as a step inside a workflow</em>, the engine builds a different
                                <code>request</code> shape (including <code>workflow_run_request</code>). That flow is documented under
                                <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-workflow-run" href="#"><code>Workflow.run</code></a>; this page focuses on <strong>direct</strong> <code>node.run(...)</code>.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p style="font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0 0.35rem"><strong>Standalone <code>request</code> — examples</strong></p>
                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0 0 0.35rem">Pass arbitrary keys; read them in <code>_on_start</code> before validation runs in <code>execute()</code>:</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python"># Caller (no engine): your keys are at the top level of request in _on_start
result = my_node.run(
    {"value": 10},
    {"scale": 2},
    request={"correlation_id": "req-9f2", "reason": "integration_test"},
)</code></pre>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_start(self, request: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; Optional[bool]:
    super()._on_start(request)
    self._correlation_id = request.get("correlation_id") or ""
    if request.get("reason") == "integration_test":
        logger.info("node %s under test correlation=%s", self.node_id, self._correlation_id)
    return True</code></pre>

                    <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0.75rem 0 0.35rem"><code>_do_execute</code> does not receive <code>request</code>. Stash what you need on <code>self</code> in <code>_on_start</code> (or read from validated <code>state</code>/<code>params</code> only):</p>
                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _on_start(self, request: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; Optional[bool]:
    super()._on_start(request)
    self._dry_run = bool(request.get("dry_run"))
    return True

def _do_execute(self, state_dict, params_dict) -&gt; NodeOutput:
    if getattr(self, "_dry_run", False):
        return NodeOutput(output={"output_format": "json", "data": {"skipped": True}})
    ...</code></pre>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        Lifecycle details: <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-overview" href="#">Event handling</a>,
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log" href="#"><code>exec_log</code></a>.
                        Orchestrated node runs (<code>WorkflowEngine.run_node</code>) add keys such as <code>execution_id</code> and <code>command</code> to the envelope they pass to <code>run()</code>—still at top level, not merged with your dict unless the engine built it that way.
                    </p>

                    <div id="section-api-node-run-dynamic" class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:1rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2v4M12 18v4M4.93 4.93l2.83 2.83M16.24 16.24l2.83 2.83M2 12h4M18 12h4M4.93 19.07l2.83-2.83M16.24 7.76l2.83-2.83"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Dynamic <code>state</code> / <code>input_params</code> (before <code>_on_init</code>)</span>
                        </div>
                        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;line-height:1.72;margin:0 0 0.5rem">
                            <code>run()</code> calls <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-start" href="#"><code>_on_start(request)</code></a> before <code>execute()</code>.
                            When you omit <code>request</code>, the framework builds <code>request</code> with the <strong>same dict objects</strong> you passed as <code>state</code> and <code>input_params</code> (for plain dicts), so you can enrich them in place inside <code>_on_start</code> and <code>_on_init</code> will still validate the updated values.
                        </p>
                        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--fx-text-muted);margin:0 0 0.35rem">Example — synchronous fetch, then mutate <code>state</code> before schema validation:</p>
                        <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">import json
import urllib.request
from typing import Any, Dict, Optional

def _on_start(self, request: Dict[str, Any]) -&gt; Optional[bool]:
    super()._on_start(request)
    st = request.get("state") or {}
    try:
        with urllib.request.urlopen("https://httpbin.org/json", timeout=5) as resp:
            st.setdefault("remote", json.loads(resp.read().decode()))
    except Exception as exc:
        self.exec_log.log("warning", f"prefetch skipped: {exc}", event="node_prefetch")
    return True</code></pre>
                        <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0.65rem">
                            <strong>Workflow steps.</strong> <code>WorkflowEngine.run_node</code> embeds <code>state</code> / <code>input_params</code> in <code>request</code> as <strong>copies</strong> for tracing; mutating <code>request["state"]</code> there does not change the <code>ObservableStateDict</code> passed as the first argument to <code>run()</code>. For dynamic behaviour inside a graph step, prefer updating workflow shared state through the engine’s state mapping, or run the node standalone with a shared <code>request</code> you control.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-load">← load</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-form-input">request_form_input →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Node — request_form_input (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-request-form-input">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run">← run()</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-cooperative-stop">request_cooperative_stop →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>request_form_input</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Shows an <strong>interactive form</strong> mid-execution inside
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-do-execute" href="#"><code>_do_execute</code></a>,
                        built from <code>input_state_schema</code> and <code>input_params_schema</code>. Unlike the automatic
                        <strong>debug</strong> form (before <code>_do_execute</code>), you call this method explicitly when you need a
                        second review step, confirmation, or reconfiguration after part of the work has run.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Requires a live <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-exec-log" href="#"><code>exec_log</code></a>
                        sink (console / Socket.IO). Without it, the call returns immediately with <code>ok=False</code> and
                        <code>status="no_channel"</code>—your node should branch (defaults, skip UX, error, etc.).
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def request_form_input(
    self,
    state_values: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None,
    params_values: Optional[Dict[str, Any]] = None,
    timeout: float = 300.0,
    title: Optional[str] = None,
) -> Dict[str, Any]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Parameters</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>state_values</code></strong> / <strong><code>params_values</code></strong> — Pre-fill the form; passed to <code>create_form_request_payload</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>timeout</code></strong> — Seconds to wait for the client (default 300).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>title</code></strong> — Optional heading; defaults to <code>"Configure &lt;name&gt;"</code>.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4"/><path d="M12 22c5.523 0 10-4.477 10-10S17.523 2 12 2 2 6.477 2 12s4.477 10 10 10z"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Return value (always a <code>dict</code>)</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>ok</code></strong> — <code>True</code> only when the user submitted successfully (<code>status="success"</code>).</li>
                            <li><strong><code>status</code></strong> — <code>success</code> | <code>cancelled</code> | <code>timeout</code> | <code>no_channel</code> | <code>error</code>.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>state</code></strong> / <strong><code>params</code></strong> — Updated values from the client when applicable; <code>None</code> on failure paths.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>detail</code></strong> / <strong><code>error_type</code></strong> — Set on <code>timeout</code>, <code>no_channel</code>, <code>error</code> (payload build or transport).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-run">← run()</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-cooperative-stop">request_cooperative_stop →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Node — request_cooperative_stop (instance method)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-request-cooperative-stop">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-form-input">← request_form_input</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-default-state-mapping">default_state_mapping →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>request_cooperative_stop</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Signals <strong>cooperative cancellation</strong> for the current node run (or for an explicit
                        <code>execution_id</code>): e.g. another thread, a timer, or in-node logic. With an execution log attached it calls
                        <code>EventLogBuffer.request_stop()</code> (sets a shared <code>threading.Event</code>). It also notifies the process-wide
                        <code>WorkflowEngine</code> via <code>get_shared_engine().stop_execution(...)</code> (lazy import) so registered runs get the same signal;
                        if the id is unknown to the engine, that part is a no-op while the buffer still receives <code>request_stop()</code>.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def request_cooperative_stop(self, execution_id: Optional[str] = None) -> None:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Execution id resolution</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Explicit <code>execution_id</code></strong> — Used as-is when provided.</li>
                            <li><strong>Else attached <code>exec_log</code></strong> — Uses <code>execution_id</code> from the buffer (engine / API runs).</li>
                            <li><strong>Else active run</strong> — While <code>execute()</code> is in progress after successful init, the node stores that run’s id internally; omitted argument still resolves in the common single-run-per-instance case.</li>
                            <li><strong>None of the above</strong> — No-op (debug log only).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <h3 class="nos-api-subheading" style="margin-top:1.25rem">What you implement: intercepting the stop in <code>_do_execute</code></h3>

                    <p>
                        Stopping is <strong>cooperative</strong>: <code>request_cooperative_stop</code> / the engine only set the flag; your code must reach a
                        <strong>checkpoint</strong>. Both patterns below are correct (see <code>docs/COOPERATIVE_EXECUTION_STOP.md</code>, §§1–7).
                    </p>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4"/><path d="M12 22c5.523 0 10-4.477 10-10S17.523 2 12 2 2 6.477 2 12s4.477 10 10 10z"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Mode 1 — Next <code>exec_log.log</code> (default)</span>
                        </div>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 0.75rem 0">
                            After <code>request_stop()</code>, <code>is_stop_requested()</code> is <code>True</code>. You do <strong>not</strong> need to call
                            <code>is_stop_requested()</code> before every <code>log</code>: the buffer checks the stop event
                            <strong>before</strong> recording the event and raises <code>CancellationError</code> if a stop was requested.
                            <code>Node.execute</code> catches that and returns <code>status="cancelled"</code>, then
                            <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-stop" href="#"><code>_on_stop</code></a> /
                            <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-lifecycle-on-end" href="#"><code>_on_end</code></a> run as usual.
                        </p>
                        <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def _do_execute(self, state_dict: dict, params_dict: dict) -&gt; NodeOutput:
    for i, url in enumerate(params_dict.get("urls") or []):
        # If stop was requested, the next log() raises CancellationError before appending the event.
        self.exec_log.log(
            "info",
            event="fetch",
            message=f"Fetching {i + 1}: {url}",
        )
        self._fetch_and_store(url)
    return NodeOutput(output={"output_format": "json", "data": {"ok": True}}, metadata={})</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.75rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 001.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 001.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 00-3.42 0z"/><path d="M12 9v4M12 17h.01"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Mode 2 — <code>is_stop_requested()</code> + <code>raise CancellationError</code></span>
                        </div>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 0.75rem 0">
                            <code>is_stop_requested()</code> only <strong>reads</strong> the flag; it does not emit a log or raise. Use it in
                            <strong>long stretches without <code>log</code></strong> (blocking I/O, heavy CPU, tight inner loops). Then
                            <code>raise CancellationError(...)</code> so you reuse the same cancellation path as Mode&nbsp;1 (do not swallow the exception).
                        </p>
                        <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">from nos.core.execution_log.event_log_buffer import CancellationError

def _do_execute(self, state_dict: dict, params_dict: dict) -&gt; NodeOutput:
    if self.exec_log.is_stop_requested():
        raise CancellationError("Stopped before slow operation")
    payload = self._slow_external_api_call(params_dict["query"])  # no log inside

    self.exec_log.log("info", event="done", message="API returned")
    return NodeOutput(
        output={"output_format": "json", "data": {"payload": payload}},
        metadata={},
    )</code></pre>
                        <p style="margin:0.75rem 0 0 0">Inside a long loop without a log every iteration, poll in the loop (same <code>raise CancellationError</code> pattern).</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.75rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Quick comparison</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-events-exec-log-log" href="#"><code>self.exec_log.log(...)</code></a></strong> — Observes stop internally; raises <code>CancellationError</code> if stop was requested. Use when you already emit progress often enough.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>self.exec_log.is_stop_requested()</code></strong> — Read-only. Use between rare logs; then <code>raise CancellationError</code> (or you delay stop until the next <code>log</code>).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <p class="nos-api-note">
                        Overlapping runs on the same <code>Node</code> instance are unusual; pass <code>execution_id</code> explicitly if you must disambiguate.
                    </p>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-form-input">← request_form_input</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-default-state-mapping">default_state_mapping →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Node — default_state_mapping (property)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-default-state-mapping">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-cooperative-stop">← request_cooperative_stop</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-set-default-state-mapping">set_default_state_mapping →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>default_state_mapping</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Optional <strong>default <code>StateMapping</code></strong> for this node when the workflow engine wires
                        links: it describes how <strong>shared workflow state</strong> is turned into this node’s input and how
                        this node’s output updates that state again. If you return <code>None</code> (and do not call
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-set-default-state-mapping" href="#"><code>set_default_state_mapping</code></a>),
                        the runtime falls back to an <strong>identity</strong> mapping when one is created lazily.
                    </p>

                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0.75rem">
                        For a narrative guide to <strong>state mapping</strong> in workflows, see
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-guide-workflow-state-mapping" href="#">State mapping</a>
                        (<em>Step-by-step Guide → Workflow</em>) — section in progress.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">@property
def default_state_mapping(self) -> Optional[StateMapping]:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Behaviour</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong>Override</strong> — Return a <code>StateMapping</code> instance on your subclass when this node should always use the same mapping unless a link overrides it.</li>
                            <li><strong><code>None</code></strong> — Identity-style default is applied when internal storage is still unset (see source <code>Node.default_state_mapping</code>).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-request-cooperative-stop">← request_cooperative_stop</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-set-default-state-mapping">set_default_state_mapping →</a>
                    </nav>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
                 PAGE: API · Node — set_default_state_mapping
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="nos-page" id="section-api-node-set-default-state-mapping">
                <div class="nos-guide-section">

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--top" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-default-state-mapping">← default_state_mapping</a>
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-output-formats"><code>output_format_schema</code> →</a>
                    </nav>

                    <header>
                        <p class="nos-section-title">API · Node · Instance methods</p>
                        <h2 class="nos-api-member-title"><code>set_default_state_mapping</code></h2>
                    </header>

                    <p>
                        Sets the node’s <strong>default state mapping</strong> at runtime (same conceptual role as the
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-default-state-mapping" href="#"><code>default_state_mapping</code></a>
                        property, but imperative). Use when tests, factories, or the workflow layer need to attach a mapping without
                        subclassing.
                    </p>

                    <p class="nos-api-note" style="margin-top:0.75rem">
                        Same topic from the guide:
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-guide-workflow-state-mapping" href="#">State mapping</a>
                        (<em>Step-by-step Guide → Workflow</em>) — section in progress.
                    </p>

                    <pre class="nos-api-signature"><code class="language-python">def set_default_state_mapping(self, mapping: Optional[StateMapping]) -> None:
    ...</code></pre>

                    <div class="nos-block-card" style="margin-top:0.5rem">
                        <div class="nos-block-card-header">
                            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5"/></svg>
                            <span class="nos-block-card-title">Parameters</span>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="nos-api-assoc">
                            <li><strong><code>mapping</code></strong> — A <code>StateMapping</code> instance, or <code>None</code> to clear the explicit override and rely on property / lazy identity behaviour.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <nav class="nos-nav-bar nos-nav-bar--bottom" aria-label="Section navigation">
                        <a class="nos-nav-page" data-section="section-api-node-default-state-mapping">← default_state_mapping</a>
